<h1 class="govuk-heading-xl">Try the Back Office Planning System (BOPS)</h1>

<div class="govuk-panel govuk-panel--confirmation ndx-walkthrough-value-prop">
  <h2 class="govuk-panel__title">
    15 minutes to experience BOPS
  </h2>
  <div class="govuk-panel__body">
    Log in as a planning officer, review live applications, and see the public-facing applicants portal.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="govuk-inset-text ndx-walkthrough-reassurance">
  <strong class="govuk-!-font-size-24">No technical knowledge required</strong>
  <p class="govuk-body">
    This walkthrough guides you through <a href="https://opendigitalplanning.org/back-office-planning-system-bops" class="govuk-link">BOPS</a> as a case officer would use it.
    You'll log in, browse planning applications, and explore the public portal.
    Perfect for planning managers, digital transformation leads, and anyone evaluating BOPS.
  </p>
</div>

<p class="govuk-body">
  The <a href="https://opendigitalplanning.org/back-office-planning-system-bops" class="govuk-link">Back Office Planning System (BOPS)</a> is the open-source planning case management system developed by the <a href="https://opendigitalplanning.org/" class="govuk-link">Open Digital Planning</a> programme. It's used by councils including Lambeth, Southwark, and Buckinghamshire to process real planning applications.
</p>

<h2 class="govuk-heading-l">What you'll do</h2>

<p class="govuk-body-l">
  In this 15-minute walkthrough, you'll:
</p>

<ol class="govuk-list govuk-list--number govuk-list--spaced">
  <li>
    <strong>Log in as a planning officer</strong> — Find your credentials and access the BOPS dashboard (2 minutes)
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Browse planning applications</strong> — See 35 realistic applications across different types and statuses (4 minutes)
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Review an application in detail</strong> — Open an application to see the full workflow: validation, consultation, assessment (5 minutes)
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Explore the applicants portal</strong> — See what the public sees, with maps and consultation deadlines (4 minutes)
  </li>
</ol>

